article.description:
Jamal Mashburn scored 25, Jamaal Magloire
added 16 points and 17 rebounds and the New Orleans Hornets
improved to 11-0 at home with a 98-96 overtime victory over the
Houston Rockets on Friday night.
article.headline: Mashburn, Magloire too much for Rockets
article.linkText: Hornets edge Rockets in OT to remain unbeaten at home
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Playing against 7-foot-6 Yao Ming and being saddled with five fouls didn't hinder Jamaal Magloire in overtime.
Magloire

Magloire scored five of his 16 points and grabbed four of his 17 rebounds in the extra period as the Hornets held off the Rockets 98-96 Friday night to improve to 11-0 at home. "He just took over at the end,'' coach Paul Silas said. "Every rebound was his ... the free throws he made -- just huge. He's really growing as a center.'' Magloire, who's 6-11, was given the starting nod at center when the season began because 7-foot Elden Campbell was out with a sprained left knee. Campbell has been back for eight games now, but Magloire continues to start. Magloire said he knew he could still be aggressive, despite the foul trouble, as long as he played smart. "We just needed to continue to play hard and go at Yao Ming to put ourselves in a good situation,'' Magloire said. Jamal Mashburn scored 25 to lead New Orleans, which is now 3-1 in overtime games. David Wesley, who was 0-for-8 for no points in his previous game, scored 19. His second 3-pointer after Baron Davis grabbed an offensive rebound gave New Orleans an 89-87 lead it would not relinquish. "That's why coaches hate when their defense gives up offensive rebounds because they always seem to come back and hurt you,'' Wesley said. "Nobody knew where I was, every one was scrambling around and I was like, I'm wide open. I'm taking this.'' Kenny Thomas came off the bench to lead Houston with a season-high 29 points and 10 rebounds. He hit an array of short jump shots, floaters and followed Steve Francis' miss with a dunk to keep Houston close late in the third period en route to its first overtime of the season. Francis scored 24 and Yao had 16 points and 13 rebounds. Even on plays when Yao didn't get the rebound, his presence helped. Several times, New Orleans rebounders stretched to slap the ball instead of grabbing rebounds cleanly as they normally would. Yao also blocked three shots. "I liked the shots I got today but I think I definitely need to get closer to the basket and get more physical inside,'' Yao said. Davis had 14 points and nine assists for New Orleans. Playing in his second game since sitting out two games with back pain, Davis appeared uninhibited and at one point in overtime got a head of steam and nearly dunked over Yao as he was fouled. New Orleans took its biggest lead, 78-69, after Brown hit a pair of free throws early in the fourth quarter, but the Hornets made only two shots from the field for the rest of the period and finished 3-of-19 for the quarter as Houston climbed into an 84-84 tie at the end of regulation. "To stay in the game with a team like this is a pretty good sign,'' Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "But I'm past signs. This could have been a big win for us.'' Mashburn scored 13 in the third quarter after missing his first five shots and scoring only four points in the first half. His 16-foot turnaround capped a stretch in which New Orleans scored on eight straight possessions and had an 11-0 run to take a 57-50 lead. The Hornets carried a 74-69 lead into the fourth quarter. After Houston started 2-for-11 from the field, Thomas brought the Rockets back with 16 points in the second quarter as the rest of his team scored 12. The Rockets took their first lead on a jumper by Thomas in the last second of the second quarter, putting them up 46-44 at the half. Game notes
New Orleans' 14-6 record is the best 20-game start to a season in Hornets history. ... Thomas doubled his 8.7-point per-game average in the first half alone, when he had 18 points off the bench. ... The Rockets did not attempt their first free throw until Thomas went to the line with 1:07 left in the first half. ... The Rockets' bench surpassed 20 points for the 11th straight game.
